rComments: Nope. He knows nothing about economics and nothing about teaching it. His test questions are stupid and unclear and he has a very strong accent which makes it hard to understand him. His stupid test questions made me nearly fail the exam. I suggest finding a different prof.

Given that I am pretty sure it was his first time teaching microeconomics, he tried his best. However, if you have no previous knowledge of micro and/or are not prepared to read the textbook and do the practice questions every week, you will probably struggle in this class. His spelling and accent may impair your ability to understand him.

Really nice guy and he's very caring. Due to his accent, he's very hard to understand. Also, he has a hard time grasping the attention of the class and makes a lot of mistakes on his slides. You need your textbook to better understand his classes.

rComments: Like everybody said he wants the best for the students. But he can't catch the attention of the class. If you want to be able to listen sit in the front, otherwise you won't understand anything. He often reads his power points and in a way is explaining to himself. Reading your textbook and doing your own thing will be your best asset.

Personally, i didn't like him very much. He was a nice guy with good intentions but his teaching skills could use some help. He's very unclear and hard to understand, doesn't give any supplementary information other than whats written in the textbook. Read the textbook and you'll be fine. Doesn't keep the attention of students. Would not take again.
Very sweet and wants the best for his students, can be confusing and unclear at times but he makes up for it with easy midterms.
PLENTY of mistakes on the power point, hard time using the microphone...
